<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-095-214  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 095 214.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Jan 29 1990 n285 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mixed feelings for computer criminal. (verdict in Robert T. MorrisJr. trial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jackson, Kelly.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Robert Morris is found guilty of violating the 1986 Computer Fraudand Abuse Act.andP;  Morris, a former Cornell University graduatestudent, introduced a secret computer program, or worm, into theInternet research network in Nov 1988.andP;  The virus replicateditself to such an extent that the research network was shut downfor a number of hours.andP;  Morris faces a maximum penalty of fiveyears in jail and a fine of $250,000.andP;  Morris' defense contendedthat he did not act in a malicious manner, and that no data wasdamaged by his experiment.andP;  The prosecution countered that asophisticated research network was no place for the experiments ofa graduate student.andP;  Computer security experts agreed that theMorris case illustrates the danger that hackers pose to computernetworks and the need for heightened security measures.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Computer Fraud and Abuse Act of 1986 (interpretation andconstruction).andO;Topic:     Law SuitComputer CrimesComputer HackersComputer VirusesInternet (Computer network).andO;Person:    Morris, Robert T., Jr. (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>